<P>A friend of yours has taken the job of security officer at the =
Star-Buy=20
Company, a famous depart- ment store. One of his tasks is to install a =
video=20
surveillance system to guarantee the security of the customers (and the =
security=20
of the merchandise of course) on all of the store's countless floors. As =
the=20
company has only a limited budget, there will be only one camera on =
every floor.=20
But these cameras may turn around to look in every direction.=20
<P>
<P><BR>The first problem is to choose where to install the camera for =
every=20
floor. The only requirement is that every part of the room must be =
visible from=20
there. In the following figure the left floor can be completely surveyed =
from=20
the position indicated by a dot, while for the right floor, there is no =
such=20
position, the given position failing to see the lower left part of the =
floor.=20
<P>
<DIV align=3Dcenter><IMG=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX00.980/p588=
.gif">=20
</DIV>
<P>Before trying to install the cameras, your friend first wants to know =
whether=20
there is indeed a suitable position for them. He therefore asks you to =
write a=20
program that, given a ground plan, de- termines whether there is a =
position from=20
which the whole floor is visible. All floor ground plans form =
rectangular=20
polygons, whose edges do not intersect each other and touch each other =
only at=20
the corners.=20
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A=20
name=3DSECTION0001001000000000000000>Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2>The =
input file=20
contains several floor descriptions. Every description starts with the =
number=20
<I>n</I> of vertices that bound the floor (=20
<!-- MATH: $4 \le=9F n \le=9F 100$ --><IMG border=3D0 alt=3D"$4 \le=9F n =
\le=9F 100$"=20
align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX00.980/588i=
mg1.gif"=20
width=3D96 height=3D30>). The next <I>n</I> lines contain two integers =
each, the=20
<I>x</I> and <I>y</I> coordinates for the <I>n</I> vertices, given in =
clockwise=20
order. All vertices will be distinct and at corners of the polygon. Thus =
the=20
edges alternate between horizontal and vertical.=20
<P>A zero value for <I>n</I> indicates the end of the input.=20
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A=20
name=3DSECTION0001002000000000000000>Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2>For =
every test=20
case first output a line with the number of the floor, as shown in the =
sample=20
output. Then print a line stating ``<TT>Surveillance is possible.</TT>'' =
if=20
there exists a position from which the entire floor can be observed, or =
print=20
``<TT>Surveillance is impossible.</TT>'' if there is no such position.=20
<P>Print a blank line after each test case.=20
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A name=3DSECTION0001003000000000000000>Sample =

Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2><PRE>4
0 0
0 1
1 1
1 0
8
0 0
0 2
1 2
1 1
2 1
2 2
3 2
3 0
0
</PRE>
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A name=3DSECTION0001004000000000000000>Sample =

Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2><PRE>Floor #1
Surveillance is possible.

Floor #2
Surveillance is impossible.
</PRE>
